		<!-- CONTENT OF THE POST -->
		<p>Boing Boing reader tw1515tw <a href="http://boingboing.net/2013/03/14/choosing-the-right-seat-how-n.html#comment-829411887">mentioned</a> this essay by mentalist <a href="http://www.google.com/cse?cx=partner-pub-2170174688585464%3Ad58nno-rqp8&#038;ie=ISO-8859-1&#038;q=derren+brown&#038;siteurl=#gsc.tab=0&#038;gsc.q=derren%20brown&#038;gsc.page=1">Derren Brown</a> on how to overcome awkward situations. Most of Brown's strategies involve behaving irrationally to disarm the other person.</p>

<p>Here's one of Brown's tips:</p>

<blockquote><p>How to handle aggressive situations

<p>This is simply about not engaging with your aggressor at the level they expect. I was coming back from a hotel at about 3am one night and there was a guy in the street with his girlfriend. He was really drunk, clearly looking for a fight and he started kicking off at me. I had a routine ready in my head for this sort of situation and it worked a treat on this occasion. He asked me that typical aggressive rhetorical question &mdash; &ldquo;Do you want a fight?&rdquo; You can&rsquo;t say &ldquo;yes&rdquo; or &ldquo;no&rdquo; &mdash; you&rsquo;ll get hit either way. So, I responded with, &ldquo;The wall outside my house is four-feet high.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I didn&rsquo;t engage at the level he was expecting me to, so immediately he was on the back foot. He came back with, &ldquo;What?&rdquo; and I repeated my bizarre response. I delivered the line in a completely matter-of-fact tone, as if he was the one who was missing something here. Suddenly, he was confused. All his adrenaline had dropped away, because I&rsquo;d pulled the rug from under him. It&rsquo;s the verbal version of a martial-arts technique called an &lsquo;adrenaline dump&rsquo;, whereby you get the person to relax before you hit them. A punch will have much greater impact if the recipient&rsquo;s guard is down. I stuck to this surreal conversational thread with my assailant, saying things like, &ldquo;I lived in Spain for a while and the walls are really huge, but in this country they&rsquo;re tiny.&rdquo; After a few of these exchanges, he just went, &ldquo;Oh f*ck!&rdquo; and broke down in tears. The guy had all this adrenaline and was on the point of really laying into me &mdash; I was seeing myself beaten to a bloody pulp &mdash; but these non-threatening nonsense statements broke that aggression down and he genuinely started crying. I ended up sitting next to him on the kerb, comforting him. It&rsquo;s the same with guys that come up and ask to &ldquo;have a look at your phone&rdquo;, and you end up handing over your stuff and hating yourself for doing it &mdash; you can use the same approach. My PA had some stuff nicked in a Tube station recently, and I said to him, &ldquo;If you&rsquo;d just starting singing, they would have left you alone.&rdquo;</p></blockquote>

<p><a href="http://www.shortlist.com/entertainment/derren-browns-guide-to-overcoming-awkward-situations">Derren Brown's guide to overcoming awkward situations</a></p>	

